[1] Mexico (Morelos)
Date: Fri 15 May 2009
Source: El Sol de Cuautla [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.oem.com.mx/elsoldecuautla/notas/n1163043.htm>


In the south zone of Morelos [state], Health
Jurisdiction II is carrying out a cleanup in
facing an outbreak of 58 cases of classical
dengue in the southern area of the state,
announced the head of this agency, Maria del
Rosario Avila Abarca. In facing the risk from the
coming rainy season, which favors the mosquito
vector of dengue [virus], the official of the
health sector, Avila Abarca, insisted that
efforts with the current municipal governments
would be redoubled for prevention. She said that
regarding trash removal and keeping patios clean,
"it is important that every house does not have
things that retain water or rain water, which
could be tires among other containers, that could
be a perfect home of the mosquito _Aedes
aegypti_." She said that "if we do not understand
the aquatic cycle for mosquito reproduction that
we are creating in our houses, we will have many
more mosquitoes and, of course, more people ill from dengue."

She indicated that so far this year [2009], the
cases have been classical dengue and hopes not to
have DHF, which could put peoples lives at risk.

[Byline: Angelina Albarran]

--
Communicated by:
Health Map Alert via
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[Involving local residents in elimination of the
water catchments that are breeding sites of
_Aedes aegypti_ in and immediately around their
houses and other buildings is the most effective
way to halt dengue virus transmission, but is
also among the most difficult measures to accomplish.

A map showing the states in Mexico can be
accessed at <http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/mexico_pol97.jpg>.
