[2] Brazil
Date: Sun 17 May 2009
Source: MDZ.online [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.mdzol.com/mdz/nota/128556-Brasil-estÃ¡-perdiendo-la-guerra-contra-la-epidemia-de-dengue/>


Brazil continues to lose the war against dengue,
to the point where more than 2000 new cases are
reported daily, while attention is focused
fundamentally on influenza A [H1N1], according to
the numbers published this Sunday [17 May 2009] in the newspaper O Globo.

No less than 14 state capitals are on alert
status, facing an avalanche of dengue cases, and
in the 1st 100 days of this year [2009], health
authorities have recorded 226 500 cases
distributed over practically the entire country.

Since the 1st day of 2009, there have now been 46
dengue deaths registered in all of Brazil,
although the numbers in recent years indicate an
increasing trend: 158 dengue deaths in 2007 and 448 in 2008.

The situation is most critical in Bahia state
(northeastern Brazil), in which a 3rd of the
recorded dengue cases [nationally] this year
[2009] have been concentrated. In this state, 2
cities, Itabuna and Camacari, are considered to
be of high risk for indexes of infection. Between
January-April 2009, the number of cases in Bahia
increased 300 percent compared to the same period
last year [2008], according to local authorities.

Beyond the increase in the number of cases and
the area where they have been recorded, the
numbers show that the velocity of propagation of
the disease is 2 times higher than that
registered just a decade ago, according to the
experts responsible for the studies.

The newspaper reported that the Coordinator of
the National Program for Dengue Control, Giovanni
Coelho, stated a week ago before the senate that
the scenario could become worse if a new dengue
[virus] type came into the country. According to
Coelho, the so-called dengue [virus] serotype 4
is predominant in Venezuela, a country with which
Brazil has intense movement of people. Because of
this, the arrival of [dengue virus type 4] is just a question of time.

--
Communicated by:
Health Map Alerts via
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[Preventing the entry and establishment of dengue
virus serotype 4 will be extremely difficult, and
Coordinator Coelho is probably correct; its arrival is just a matter of time.

ProMED-PORT posted the original O Globo report (in Portuguese) of 16 May 2009
<http://oglobo.globo.com/cidades/mat/2009/05/16/dengue-se-alastra-pelo-pais-multiplica-mortes-em-dez-anos-755896295.asp>,
followed by the comment from Mod.LJS saying: "Sad
but true. What is sad is not the fact this
occurs, but rather we are seeing assertion of the
good news that the number of cases is 49 percent
lower than the previous year. We are not living
with a competition in which the best score is
given to the lowest number of cases, and so are not confronting dengue."

A map of Brazil showing the states can be
accessed at <http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/brazil.jpg>.
The state of Bahia can be located on the
HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Brazil
at <http://healthmap.org/r/008M>. - Mod.TY]

