[4] Malaysia
Thu 14 May 2009
Source: Malaysian National News Agency (Bernama) [edited]
<http://www.bernama.com/bernama/v5/newsindex.php?id=411087>


In the week ending 9 May [2009], 5 deaths due to
dengue fever were recorded, bringing to 48 the
number of people who have died of the disease so
far this year [2009]. Director General of Health
Tan Sri Dr Mohd Ismail Merican said there was
also a rise in the number of dengue fever cases
in the country during that week, to 874 from 870
in the previous week, ending 2 May [2009]. "The
number of cumulative cases so far this year is 19
275 compared to 13 891 with 33 deaths in the same
period last year," he said in a statement Thursday [14 May 2009].

He said 7 states recorded an increase in the
number of cases so far this year [2009], with
Kedah registering 9, Kelantan 8, Johor 23, Penang
22, Kuala Lumpur and Putrajaya 20, Melaka 3 and Perak 13.

Up to 9 May [2009], 63 hotspots were reported,
with 57 of the localities in Selangor, 4 in Kuala
Lumpur and Putrajaya and the rest in Johor, he
said. "The people in these localities are advised
to keep their houses and surroundings clean and
destroy breeding places of the _Aedes_ mosquito,
carrier of the dengue virus," he said.

Dr Mohd Ismail said 579 compound fines totaling
RM 68 850 [USD 19 451] were imposed and 201
clean-up notices were issued nationwide in the
week ending 9 May [2009] to owners of premises
found to harbor _Aedes_ breeding places and
potential breeding places. He said 71 percent of
the houses and shops inspected were found to
harbor _Aedes_ breeding places, as well as 19 per
cent of factories, 17 per cent of burial grounds
and road dividers, and 14 per cent of
construction sites. "This shows that a large
number of people are not yet sensitive to the
danger of _Aedes_ breeding places in their houses
and surroundings. The gotong-royong (self-help)
activities have not achieved their target,
because only 70 percent of the targeted 76
activities could be undertaken last week," he said.

--
